# .gitignore (Terraform)
# Excludes files that should NEVER be committed to git.
#
# Two main categories:
#   1. State files -- contain a snapshot of your AWS resources, possibly with
#      sensitive metadata. Treat like passwords.
#   2. Variable files with real values -- may contain secrets, account IDs,
#      bucket names that vary per user.

# Terraform state files -- LOCAL ONLY, never commit.
# In a team setup, state would be stored remotely (S3 + DynamoDB).
*.tfstate
*.tfstate.*
*.tfstate.backup

# Crash log
crash.log
crash.*.log

# Real variable values -- gitignored so each user provides their own.
# The .example file IS committed as a template.
*.tfvars
*.tfvars.json
!*.tfvars.example

# Local plan output -- can contain sensitive info if you save a plan to disk
*.tfplan

# Provider plugins and modules cache -- downloaded by `terraform init`,
# can be regenerated, so no point committing (large + redundant).
.terraform/
.terraform.lock.hcl.bak

# CLI configuration (rare, but just in case)
.terraformrc
terraform.rc

# macOS junk
.DS_Store
